The William J. Carroll Government Center is located within the Brown’s Valley area of the City of
Vacaville at the northeast corner of the intersection of East Monte Vista Avenue and Brown Street
in Solano County, California. It is proposed that the 2.78 acre County-owned site consist of the
construction of a new two-story, 35,000 square foot Public Health Facility and Clinic for the Solano
County Health and Social Services Department to house social services and clinical uses. The site
is currently bounded by a single family residence and City of Vacaville-owned land to the west,
City-owned land to the north, the Monte Vista Mobile Home Park to the east, and East Monte Vista
The existing circulation network consists of freeways, arterial streets, collector streets and local
streets. While not specifically described in the City of Vacaville General Plan (December 2007),
the following are typical definitions for the street classifications.
Freeways and expressways are typically major divided highways designed for high-speed travel
Arterial streets are designed to primarily serve intra-urban travel, collecting traffic from lower
order streets and conveying it to and from other parts of the City. Access to abutting property is
subordinate to the primary function of moving traffic.
Collector streets are designed to serve neighborhood traffic, providing links between local streets
and arterials, and access to abutting property.
Local streets intended to provide direct access to destinations within a residential or business district
and provide access to abutting property as a primary function.
The locations studied in this evaluation are located in the City of Vacaville and consist of arterials
and collectors. Streets near the project area and in the surrounding area which may be affected by
Allison Drive is a four- to six-lane roadway classified as an arterial through the study area located
to the east of the project site. Allison Drive provides regional access to the study area via a full
interchange at I-80. The posted speed limit is 40 mph north of East Monte Vista Avenue and 35
mph south of East Monte Vista Avenue.
Brown Street is a two-lane roadway with on-street parking that is classified as an arterial located to
the west of the project site. Brown Street travels north-south through the City between East Monte
Vista Avenue and Browns Valley Parkway. The posted speed limit is 25 mph.
Callen Street is a two-lane roadway classified as a collector with on-street parking south of the site
that travels in a circuitous route through the study area and intersects East Monte Vista Avenue at
two locations east and west of the site. The posted speed limit is 25 mph.
Depot Street is a four-lane roadway classified as an arterial between I-80 and East Monte Vista
Avenue which provides regional access to the study area via a partial interchange at I-80. There are
bike lanes along Depot Street between Mason Street and East Monte Vista Avenue; however, the
northbound bike lane striping ends south of the intersection. The posted speed limit is 35 mph.
East Monte Vista Avenue is a four-lane roadway classified as an arterial located directly to the
south of the project site. East Monte Vista Avenue generally travels east-west through the City and
will provide local access to the project site via two driveways. The posted speed limit is 30 mph.
Markham Avenue is a two-lane roadway classified as a collector that travels north-south within
the study area west of the site. The posted speed limit is 25 mph.
Mason Street is a four- to six-lane roadway classified as an arterial through the study area west of
the site. The posted speed limit is 30 mph west of Depot Street and 35 mph east of Depot Street.
Scoggins Court is a two-lane local street that provided direct access to residential developments
west of the site. The posted speed limit is 25 mph.

This section assesses vehicular traffic on roadways and at intersections, using both level of service
calculations and signal warrant tests. These terms are described below.
Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative term describing operating conditions a driver will experience
while traveling on a particular street or at an intersection during a specific time interval. It ranges
from LOS A (very little delay) to LOS F (long delays and congestion).
definition for each level of service category.
Free flow with no delays. Users are virtually unaffected by others in the traffic stream.
At signalized intersections, turning movements are easily made and all queues clear in a
Stable traffic. Traffic flows smoothly with few delays. An occasional approach phase is
fully utilized. Drivers begin to feel somewhat restricted within platoons of vehicles.
Stable flow but the operation of individual users becomes affected by other vehicles.
Modest delays. Major approach phases fully utilized. Backups may develop behind
Approaching unstable flow. Operation of individual users becomes significantly affected
by other vehicles. Delays may be more than one cycle during peak hours. Queues may
develop but dissipate rapidly, without excessive delays.
Unstable flow with operating conditions at or near the capacity level. Long delays and
Forced or breakdown flow that causes reduced capacity. Traffic demand exceeds the
capacity. Stop and go traffic conditions. Excessive long delays and vehicle queuing.

The City of Vacaville evaluates intersection levels of service using the methodology of the
Transportation Research Board’s Intersection Capacity Utilization (ICU) Method from
Transportation Research Circular 212, 1980. Utilizing this methodology, the level of service at
each intersection is calculated comparing the total traffic volume at an intersection to the entire
intersection’s vehicular capacity. The level of service corresponds to the ratio of total traffic
volume on the facility to the maximum capacity of volume allowable on that facility. Table 2
summarizes the relationship between the level of service rating and the volume to capacity ratio for

Traffic signals are used to provide an orderly flow of traffic through an intersection. Many times,
they are needed to offer side street traffic an opportunity to access a major road where high volumes
and/or high vehicle speeds impede crossing or turn movements. Signals do not, however, increase
the capacity of an intersection. In fact, they often slightly reduce the number of total vehicles that
can pass through an intersection in a given period of time. Signals can also cause an increase in
traffic accidents if installed at inappropriate locations.
Tests for determining whether a traffic signal should be considered for installation have been
developed. These tests, called “warrants,” consider criteria such as traffic volume, pedestrian
volume, presence of school children, and accident history. There are eleven warrants used in the
State of California in deciding whether to install a traffic signal. Usually, two or more warrants
must be met before a signal is considered. Warrant #3 is for Peak Hour Volumes. An intersection
meets Warrant #3 when peak hourly volumes on the major street and the minor street exceed
specified values for any one hour of an average day. When an intersection meets Warrant #3, there
is a strong indication that a detailed signal warrant analysis covering all possible warrants is
appropriate, as described in the 2003 Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD) and
the California supplement to the 2003 MUTCD. In areas with populations of less than 10,000 or at
locations where speeds on an uncontrolled intersection approach are greater than 40 miles per hour,
a rural peak hour warrant is used for evaluation. At all other locations, an urban warrant is used for
It is possible that an unsignalized intersection will not meet signal warrants, even though one or
more movements may experience LOS F operations. Although vehicles stopped on minor streets
may experience long delays of one minute or more, there would not be an overall benefit if the
higher numbers of vehicles on the major street were stopped in favor of the few vehicles on the
minor street. The signal warrant analysis balances major street and minor street delays, and may
indicate that there is overall benefit if drivers for some turn movements from the minor street
continue to experience (LOS E or F) delays.

The County has chosen to analyze the impacts of the project in accordance with standards
established by the City of Vacaville. The City has adopted thresholds of significance for traffic
impact analyses, identified in Title 14, Land Use and Development Code of the Vacaville Municipal
Code. Traffic impacts would be considered significant if:

The volume to capacity ratio at an intersection operating at LOS E or F in the baseline
condition would be increased by 0.02 or greater due to traffic generated from the proposed
Impact criteria for bicycle and pedestrian facilities and transit system are in accordance with
standard engineering practices. Pedestrian impacts are considered significant if the project disrupts
existing, or interferes with planned pedestrian facilities, creates a high demand for pedestrians at
locations that lack pedestrian facilities, or creates inconsistencies with adopted pedestrian system
plans, guidelines, policies, or standards. Bicycle impacts are considered significant if the project
disrupts existing, or interferes with planned bicycle facilities, or creates inconsistencies with
adopted pedestrian system plans, guidelines, policies, or standards. Transit impacts are considered
significant if the project disrupts existing, or interferes with planned transit services or facilities,
creates demand for public transit services above that which is provided or planned, or creates
inconsistencies with adopted transit system plans, guidelines, policies, or standards.

the weekday AM and PM peak hour trip generation for the proposed WJC Government Center
project. Several different ITE land use codes (LUC) were researched to estimate a reasonable trip
generating potential for the site, including Government Office Building (LUC 730), Clinic (LUC
630), and Medical-Dental Office (LUC 720). General Office (LUC 710) was also researched and

While technically a government office building, the services being provided in the proposed
development are more comparable to a clinic or medical office. ITE describes a clinic as any
facility that provides limited diagnostic and outpatient care, but is unable to provide prolonged in-
house medical and surgical care. ITE also describes medical office as a facility that provides
diagnoses and outpatient care on a routine basis, but is unable to provide prolonged in-house
The trip generation data for clinics is very limited based on square footage as the independent
variable – only one study conducted to estimate weekday PM peak hour trip generation, two
studies to estimate daily trip generation, and no data for weekday AM peak hour. It is unknown
at this time the number of employees or full-time doctors that will be employed at this facility;
therefore, these independent variables cannot be utilized to estimate trip generation.
The data to estimate trip generation for medical-dental office is greater, with numerous studies
conducted to estimate trip generation for this particular use. Therefore, for the purposes of this
study, the trip generation will be estimated utilizing the Medical-Dental Office ITE land use code.

This section evaluates the traffic impacts of buildout of the proposed project under Near Term
traffic and roadway conditions. The Near Term scenario without the addition of the project
generated traffic establishes a baseline condition with the project’s impacts will be evaluated. It
represents traffic conditions that are projected to exist once development that has been approved is
built and occupied. In conjunction with the City of Vacaville transportation department, a number
of approved projects were identified within the City. These approved projects were determined to
add traffic to the study area intersections and modify existing travel patterns. The Near Term Plus
Project scenario will add the project generated trips to the projected Near Term traffic volumes to
determine potential impact due to the project.
The Near Term traffic volumes at the study area intersections were estimated by using growth rates
derived from the City of Vacaville travel demand forecasting model. Land use data is included in
the model on a traffic analysis zone (TAZ) level of detail. Model trip generation is performed with
algorithms that reflect land use assumptions, roadway network data, and calibrated trip rates
specific to the area. The model’s trip generation is “calibrated” to match local conditions. Using
the land use and network (street and intersection) data, the model distributes or allocates trips
to/from each TAZ, or land use area. The model then assigns the trips to the roadway network based
on least cost (time and/or distance) path. The model output is in the form of directional link
volumes for weekday AM and PM peak periods. The City then post-processes the link volumes to
project turning movement volumes at an intersection.
Model output files, including intersection turning movement projections, were received from the
City and utilized to develop future traffic projections. Volumes from the model were used to
forecast weekday AM and PM peak hour volumes for the Near Term No Project scenario. To
develop peak hour turning movement volumes at each of the study area intersections, a comparison
of the base year model volumes and future year model volumes generates a growth rate for each
movement. It is anticipated that this growth rate will account for both general traffic growth in the
area as well as future variations in travel patterns. The individual movement growth rates will be
applied to the existing traffic counts provided by the City of Vacaville to project future AM and PM
peak hour volumes at the study area intersections for the Near Term No Project scenario. The Near
Term No Project traffic volumes and are shown in Figure 4. Additional detail depicting the
development of the Near Term traffic volumes is included in the Appendix.

The project will have a significant impact at the intersection of East Monte Vista Avenue/Depot
Street/Markham Avenue, based on an increase in the volume to capacity ratio by 0.02 with the
Mitigation Measure TRAF-3: A substantial number of left turns are projected in the eastbound
and westbound direction along East Monte Vista Avenue at Depot Street. However, these left
turns are served by a single left turn lane resulting in high volume to capacity ratios for these
movements. There are two potential options to mitigate the impacts.
Option 1: Reconfigure approach lanes and modify the traffic operations of the signalized
intersection. Reconfigure the inside, eastbound through lane to a shared through/left turn lane
and the inside westbound through lane to a shared through/left turn lane. Provide split phasing
for the eastbound and westbound approaches. This modification results in a volume to capacity
ratio of 0.97, LOS E, reducing the project impact to equal the conditions under the Cumulative
No Project scenario. With this mitigation, the impact would be reduced to less-than-significant.
Option 2: Reconstruct the intersection to accommodate dual left turn lanes in the eastbound and
westbound directions. This option would potentially require additional right of way from
adjacent private property. The resulting volume to capacity ratio would be 0.86, LOS D. With
this mitigation, the impact would be reduced to less-than-significant.

Trip Generation and Trip Distribution Summary
Kimley-Horn and Associates, Inc. (Kimley-Horn) has been retained by Michael
Brandman Associates to prepare a traffic study for the proposed William J. Carroll
(WJC) Government Center. The project site is located within the Brown’s Valley area
of the City of Vacaville near the northeast corner of the intersection of East Monte
Vista Avenue and Brown Street. It is proposed that the 2.78 acre County-owned site

The purpose of this memo is to present the proposed trip generation and trip
distribution for the project for approval by Solano County and the City of Vacaville.
Trip generation rates are based on an independent variable used to the estimate the trip
generating potential of a particular land use. The independent variable could include
The Institute of Transportation Engineers’ (ITE), Trip Generation, 8
used to derive the weekday AM and PM peak hour trip generation for the proposed
WJC Government Center project. Several different ITE land use codes (LUC) were
researched to estimate a reasonable trip generating potential for the site, including
Government Office Building (LUC 730), Clinic (LUC 630), and Medical-Dental
William J. Carroll Government Center Trip Generation, November 12, 2009, Page 2
Office (LUC 720). General Office (LUC 710) was also researched and used only as a
While technically a government office building, the services being provided in the
proposed development are more comparable to a clinic or medical office. ITE
describes a clinic as any facility that provides limited diagnostic and outpatient care,
but is unable to provide prolonged in-house medical and surgical care. ITE also
describes medical office as a facility that provides diagnoses and outpatient care on a
routine basis, but is unable to provide prolonged in-house medical and surgical care.
The trip generation data for clinics is very limited based on square footage as the
independent variable – only one study conducted to estimate weekday PM peak hour
trip generation, two studies to estimate daily trip generation, and no data for weekday
AM peak hour. It is unknown at this time the number of employees or full-time
doctors that will be employed at this facility; therefore, these independent variables
cannot be utilized to estimate trip generation.
The data to estimate trip generation for medical-dental office is greater, with
numerous studies conducted to estimate trip generation for this particular use.
Therefore, for the purposes of this study, the trip generation will be estimated utilizing
the Medical-Dental Office ITE land use code.
There is a transit line that operates along Brown Street and East Monte Vista Avenue
with stops currently along East Monte Vista Avenue east of the project site. To be
conservative, no reductions were applied to the trip generation of the site attributable
to the potential use of transit to access the site.

Exhibit 2 shows the traffic distribution assumed for this traffic study.

demand forecasting model in addition to base and future year peak hour turning
movement projections for the study area intersections. To develop future year no
project peak hour turning movement volumes, the base model volumes will be
compared to the future year model volumes to calculate a growth rate for each
movement at the study area intersections for both the AM and PM peak hours. It is
anticipated that this growth rate will account for both general traffic growth in the area
as well as future variations in travel patterns. The individual movement growth rates
